From 443398583377c2a758557055f128b3d256ebdf0f Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nadia Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@ik.me>
Date: Wed, 13 May 2026 01:35:47 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 113/174] mips: align mips_stack_top() down to PAGE_SIZE for
 PGCL safety
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The intermediate subtractions inside mips_stack_top() are MMUPAGE-sized
(VDSO_NR_PAGES * MMUPAGE_SIZE, optional GIC MMUPAGE, shm_align_mask + 1
which is also MMUPAGE-sized).  Without PGCL these are equivalent to
PAGE-sized subtractions, so the result is always PAGE-aligned.  Under
PGCL (PAGE_SIZE > MMUPAGE_SIZE), `top` can end up MMUPAGE-aligned but
not PAGE-aligned.

That matters because arch_setup_additional_pages() shortly afterwards
does:

    do_mmap(NULL, STACK_TOP, PAGE_SIZE,
            PROT_READ | PROT_EXEC,
            MAP_ANONYMOUS | MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_FIXED, 0, 0, ...)

for the FP-emu delay-slot page.  When STACK_TOP is sub-PAGE-aligned, the
MAP_FIXED mapping at length PAGE_SIZE silently overlaps the upper
kernel-page of the user stack — exactly the kernel-page where
copy_strings just placed argv/env.  The new anonymous mapping's
page-table install zeroes that kernel-page, busybox-as-init sees
argv[0]="" and exits 127, the kernel panics with "Attempted to kill
init! exitcode=0x00007f00".

The failure rate at PAGE_MMUSHIFT=6 was about 12-25 % per boot.
Aligning STACK_TOP down to PAGE_SIZE fixes it deterministically
(25/25 boots clean in stress testing).

Tracked down by stepping copy_from_user(bprm->p, ...) probes through
begin_new_exec → relocate_vma_down → expand_stack_locked → each
elf_load → arch_setup_additional_pages → create_elf_tables →
mips/start_thread; the argv bytes were intact at every probe up to
"before arch_setup_additional_pages" and zero at every probe from
"after arch_setup_additional_pages" onward.  Bisecting the inside of
arch_setup_additional_pages with `if (0 && IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_MIPS_FP_SUPPORT))`
took the failure rate from 12 % to 0/30, isolating the FP-emu
do_mmap as the corrupting step.

The cost of this alignment is at most PAGE_SIZE - MMUPAGE_SIZE bytes
of unused virtual address space at the top of every user mm — about
1 MB out of TASK_SIZE = 1 TB on mips64 PGCL=6.  Invisible.

Signed-off-by: Nadia Yvette Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@gmail.com>
---
 arch/mips/kernel/process.c | 12 +++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 11 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/arch/mips/kernel/process.c b/arch/mips/kernel/process.c
index 1519846c2ca0..1ddcfca99ad6 100644
--- a/arch/mips/kernel/process.c
+++ b/arch/mips/kernel/process.c
@@ -704,7 +704,17 @@ unsigned long mips_stack_top(void)
 	if (cpu_has_dc_aliases)
 		top -= shm_align_mask + 1;
 
-	return top;
+	/*
+	 * Under PGCL the intermediate subtractions above are MMUPAGE-sized
+	 * (e.g. 16 KB at PAGE_MMUSHIFT=6), so `top` may end up MMUPAGE-aligned
+	 * but not PAGE-aligned.  arch_setup_additional_pages later does
+	 * do_mmap(STACK_TOP, PAGE_SIZE, MAP_FIXED) for the FP-emu delay-slot
+	 * page; with a non-PAGE-aligned start that mapping clobbers the
+	 * kernel-page that holds the upper end of the user stack — exactly
+	 * where copy_strings just placed argv/env.  Round down so STACK_TOP
+	 * is always PAGE-aligned.
+	 */
+	return top & PAGE_MASK;
 }
 
